    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-02-11T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-02-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="497"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d497">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.1216M/2257</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Mexico</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bursley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Adviser on Political Relations</hi>
                        (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Duggan</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-02-11">February 11,
                            1943</date>.<lb/>[Received February 13.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Larry</hi>: I refer to my letter of February 10th
                    regarding the water matter.</p>
                <p>I have just found time to read the latest batch of papers from the Department
                    regarding the Colorado River question, and note on page 4 of Dr. Timm’s<note
                        n="13" xml:id="d497fn13">Charles A. Timm, Divisional Assistant, Division of
                        the American Republics.</note> memorandum of conversation dated January
                        25th<note n="14" xml:id="d497fn14">Not printed.</note> a reference to the
                    risk we might run were this matter ever submitted to international
                    arbitration.</p>
                <p>The reference to the possibility that Mexico might make a cut just below the
                    upper boundary smacks somewhat of Federal Project No. 5 on the Rio Grande.<note
                        n="15" xml:id="d497fn15">A proposed valley gravity canal and storage project
                        for the lower Rio Grande valley in Texas.</note> That is to say, it would be
                    difficult for our Government to object should Mexico undertake the cut on the
                    Colorado River in Mexican territory.</p>
                <p>Sincerely yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Herb</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
